7 Display Styles
****************

Simply Annotate supports five display styles that can be used
individually or combined as a list.  Styles are processed in order, so
later face-based styles override earlier ones while fringe styles are
independent.

7.1 Available Styles
====================

‘highlight’
     Traditional background highlighting of annotated text (good for
     emphasis)
‘tint’
     Subtle background colour derived from the current theme, lightened
     by ‘simply-annotate-tint-amount’ (default 5%).  Adapts
     automatically to any theme.
‘fringe’
     Shows small indicators in the left fringe (minimal visual impact)
‘fringe-bracket’
     Draws a vertical bracket in the left fringe spanning the full
     annotated region.  Uses the configured fringe indicator at the top
     with a continuous vertical bar and a horizontal cap at the bottom.
     Customisable via ‘simply-annotate-fringe-bracket-face’.

‘bar’
     Draws a solid heavy vertical bar (‘┃ ’) in the left margin of every
     annotated line.

‘bracket’
     Outlines annotated regions with heavy box-drawing corners (‘┏ ’, ‘┃
     ’, ‘┗ ’) for multi-line annotations, or a single ‘┠ ’ indicator for
     single-line annotations.  This is now the default display style.

‘subtle’
     Uses overline and underline to bracket annotated regions
     (unobtrusive)

7.2 Combining Styles
====================

Styles can be combined by setting ‘simply-annotate-display-style’ to a
list:

     (setq simply-annotate-display-style '(highlight fringe))
     (setq simply-annotate-display-style '(tint fringe-bracket))

   Additionally, inline display can be toggled on top of any style
(*note Display Styles::).

7.3 Changing Display Styles
===========================

You can change the display style in several ways:

   • Press ‘M-s '’ to cycle through all three styles
   • Set ‘simply-annotate-display-style’ in your configuration
   • Use ‘simply-annotate-update-display-style’ to refresh existing
     annotations

7.4 Style Recommendations
=========================

*Code Review*
     Use ‘fringe’ style to avoid visual clutter while coding
*Research and Documentation*
     Use ‘highlight’ style for emphasis on important passages
*Critical Files*
     Use ‘both’ style for maximum visibility of important annotations
*Code Exploration*
     Toggle inline display (‘M-s /’) to read annotations in context
     without opening the annotation buffer
*Threading Display*
     All styles work well with threaded annotations and status
     indicators

7.5 Fringe Customization
========================

The fringe display can be customized:

   • Choose different symbols: ‘left-triangle’, ‘right-triangle’,
     ‘filled-rectangle’, or ‘custom’
   • Customize colors with ‘simply-annotate-fringe-face’
   • Define custom bitmaps for unique indicators

7.6 Inline Display
==================

Inline display is an overlay that can be toggled on top of any display
style with ‘M-s /’ (‘simply-annotate-toggle-inline’).  When active, it
renders annotation text as a box-drawn block relative to the annotated
region.

   The position is controlled by ‘simply-annotate-inline-position’:

‘after’
     (Default) The block appears after the annotated region:

          (defun calculate-total (items)
            ┌─ ✎ [OPEN/NORMAL] ────────
            │ Sums all item prices.
            │ Returns zero for empty list.
            └────────────────────────────
            (apply #'+ (mapcar #'price items)))

‘above’
     The block appears above the annotated region:

            ┌─ ✎ [OPEN/NORMAL] ────────
            │ Sums all item prices.
            │ Returns zero for empty list.
            └────────────────────────────
          (defun calculate-total (items)
            (apply #'+ (mapcar #'price items)))

   Both inline blocks and the underlying display style (highlight,
fringe, both, or subtle) are filtered to the active annotation level --
cycling levels with ‘M-s [’ updates which annotations are visible.

   Long annotations are truncated after
‘simply-annotate-inline-max-lines’ lines (default 20).  Thread metadata
(status, priority, comment count) appears in the header.

7.6.1 Inline Pointer
--------------------

A pointer connects each inline box to the annotated text, making the
association visually clear.  The pointer string is indented to the
annotation start column.  Strings can be multiline (use ‘\n’).  Set to
‘nil’ or an empty string to disable.

‘simply-annotate-inline-pointer-after’
     Pointer shown between annotated text and the box below.  Default:
     ‘"▴"’
‘simply-annotate-inline-pointer-above’
     Pointer shown between the box above and annotated text.  Default:
     ‘"▾"’

   Example pointer styles (see the Commentary section for a full list):

     ;; Simple arrows (default)
     (setq simply-annotate-inline-pointer-after "▴")
     (setq simply-annotate-inline-pointer-above "▾")

     ;; Heavy L-bracket
     (setq simply-annotate-inline-pointer-after "┃\n┗━▶")
     (setq simply-annotate-inline-pointer-above "┏━▶\n┃")

     ;; Disabled
     (setq simply-annotate-inline-pointer-after nil)
     (setq simply-annotate-inline-pointer-above nil)

7.6.2 Inline Customisation
--------------------------

Customise the appearance with:

   • ‘simply-annotate-inline-face’: face for the annotation body text
   • ‘simply-annotate-inline-border-face’: face for the box-drawing
     border
   • ‘simply-annotate-inline-max-lines’: maximum lines before truncation
   • ‘simply-annotate-inline-position’: ‘'after’ or ‘'above’
   • ‘simply-annotate-inline-pointer-after’: pointer string for ‘'after’
     position
   • ‘simply-annotate-inline-pointer-above’: pointer string for ‘'above’
     position


