10 Advanced Features
********************

10.1 Listing All Annotations
============================

To see an overview of all annotations in the current buffer:

     M-s l

   The listing uses org-mode for full folding support.  The structure
is:

     #+TITLE: Annotations for myfile.el
     #+STARTUP: show2levels

     * FILE (1)
     ** [OPEN/NORMAL] Line 1 (1 comment)
     *** Region
     ~;; file header comment~
     *** Comment - james dyer (06/19 09:49)
     Overall file description

     * DEFUN (2)
     ** [OPEN/HIGH] Line 15 review (2 comments)
     *** Region
     ~(defun calculate-total ()~
     *** Comment - james dyer (06/19 09:49)
     This needs review before release
     *** Reply - jane smith (06/19 10:15)
     I'll check this today

   Use ‘TAB’ and ‘S-TAB’ for org folding.  Within the listing buffer:

   • ‘n’ - move to next annotation and jump to source
   • ‘p’ - move to previous annotation and jump to source
   • ‘RET’ - jump to source location of annotation at point
   • ‘q’ - quit the listing buffer

   The listing automatically refreshes when annotations are modified
(saved, edited, replied to, removed, or have properties changed).

10.2 Global Annotation Overview
===============================

To see all annotations across all files in a single org-mode buffer,
bind ‘simply-annotate-show-all’ globally:

     (global-set-key (kbd "C-c 0") #'simply-annotate-show-all)

   This produces a ‘*All Annotations*’ buffer with files as top-level
headings:

     #+TITLE: All Annotations
     #+STARTUP: content

     * ~/project/myfile.el (3)
     ** FILE (1)
     *** [OPEN/NORMAL] Line 1 (1 comment)
     ** DEFUN (2)
     *** [OPEN/HIGH] Line 15 review (2 comments)

     * ~/project/other.el (5)
     ** DEFUN (3)
     ...

   The same ‘n’/‘p’/‘RET’/‘q’ navigation works here.  Jumping to an
annotation opens the source file in another window.

10.3 Cross-Project Overview
===========================

When annotations are spread across multiple projects, you can use the
cross-project overview to discover them all in one place.  Press ‘M-s A’
(‘simply-annotate-list-projects’) from any buffer, or access it through
the command map prefix.

   This produces a ‘*Annotation Projects*’ buffer showing a sortable
table of every project that has annotations, with per-status counts so
you can see at a glance where open work is concentrated.

10.3.1 Columns
--------------

The table has the following columns (all sortable by clicking the header
or pressing ‘S’ on the column):

‘Project’
     Project name (last component of the project root).
‘Files’
     Number of annotated files in the project.
‘Ann’
     Total annotation count across all files in the project.
‘Status columns’
     One numeric column per entry in ‘simply-annotate-thread-statuses’,
     showing how many annotations are currently in that state.  Headers
     are abbreviated to the initials of each word in the status name so
     the table stays compact:

     Header         Status
     ----------------------------------------------------
     ‘O’            ‘open’
     ‘IP’           ‘in-progress’
     ‘R’            ‘resolved’
     ‘C’            ‘closed’

     If you customize ‘simply-annotate-thread-statuses’ to add a value
     like ‘needs-review’, a new column headed ‘NR’ appears
     automatically.  Legacy (pre-thread) string annotations are counted
     as ‘open’.
‘Path’
     Abbreviated absolute path of the project root.

10.3.2 Actions
--------------

From this table you can drill down into any project:

‘RET’
     Open the sortable project table for the project at point
‘L’
     Open the org-mode listing for the project at point
‘K’
     Open the Kanban board for the project at point
‘g’
     Refresh the project list
‘q’
     Quit the overview

10.3.3 Discovery
----------------

The projects shown are discovered from two sources, merged by project
root:

  1. The global annotation database (‘simply-annotate-file’), with
     absolute file keys resolved to project roots via ‘project.el’.
  2. Every project root known to ‘project.el’
     (‘project-known-project-roots’, the same list that backs
     ‘project-switch-project’) that contains a per-project annotation
     file (‘simply-annotate-project-file’, default
     ‘.simply-annotations.el’) at its root.

   This means the overview works regardless of whether you use
‘simply-annotate-database-strategy’ set to ‘global’, ‘project’, or
‘both’.  If a project uses the per-project strategy but is not yet in
your ‘project.el’ known list, visit any file inside it once (or call
‘project-remember-project’) so it shows up.

   Drill-down actions read the target project's annotations directly
from its own database file, so you can browse annotations from any
project without first switching to it.

10.4 Quick File Jump
====================

For quick navigation without the full overview, bind
‘simply-annotate-jump-to-file’ globally:

     (global-set-key (kbd "C-c 9") #'simply-annotate-jump-to-file)

   This uses ‘completing-read’ to show all annotated files with counts,
opens the selected file, and enables ‘simply-annotate-mode’.

10.5 Dired Integration
======================

Enable ‘simply-annotate-dired-mode’ in dired buffers to show fringe
indicators next to files that have annotations in the database:

     ;; Enable for all dired buffers
     (add-hook 'dired-mode-hook #'simply-annotate-dired-mode)

   The fringe indicator uses the same symbol and face as annotation
markers in source buffers (‘simply-annotate-fringe-indicator’ and
‘simply-annotate-fringe-face’).  Indicators refresh automatically when
the dired buffer is re-read (e.g. after pressing ‘g’).

10.6 Annotation Buffer Features
===============================

The annotation buffer provides a rich editing environment with threading
support:

   • Shows helpful instructions with threading commands in the header
   • Displays thread information, status, and priority
   • Shows complete conversation thread with replies
   • Access to threading commands (‘M-s r’, ‘M-s s’, ‘M-s p’, ‘M-s t’)
   • Access to advanced sexp editing with ‘M-s e’
   • Supports multi-line annotations with full editing capabilities
   • Starts in edit mode for immediate typing
   • Provides save (‘C-c C-c’) and cancel (‘C-c C-k’) operations
   • Automatically handles empty annotations (removes them)

10.7 Header-line Integration
============================

The header-line provides real-time information with threading support:

   • Active annotation level indicator (‘[FILE]’, ‘[DEFUN]’, or
     ‘[LINE]’)
   • Current annotation position scoped to the active level (e.g.,
     "2/5")
   • Thread status and priority (e.g., ‘[OPEN/HIGH:3]’)
   • Total annotation count for the active level
   • Enhanced keybinding help including threading and level commands
   • Context-sensitive help text
   • Automatic updates when annotations, threads, or levels change


