12 Kanban Board
***************

The kanban board (‘M-s K’ or ‘simply-annotate-kanban’) displays project
annotations as cards arranged in columns by status.  It requires a
project detectable by ‘project.el’.

12.1 Board Layout
=================

The board renders four columns corresponding to the thread statuses
(‘open’, ‘in-progress’, ‘resolved’, ‘closed’).  Each card shows:

   • Priority indicator with colour coding (critical = red, high =
     orange, etc.)
   • First line of the annotation text as a summary
   • Source file and line number

      OPEN (3)            IN-PROGRESS (1)     RESOLVED (0)        CLOSED (0)
     ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
     ┌──────────────────┐ ┌──────────────────┐
     │ [normal] Review.. │ │ [high] Fix bug.. │
     │ src/main.el:42   │ │ src/util.el:15   │
     └──────────────────┘ └──────────────────┘
     ┌──────────────────┐
     │ [low] Add docs.. │
     │ README.org:10    │
     └──────────────────┘

12.2 Navigation
===============

Navigation follows an org-table-style grid:

‘TAB’
     Move to the same row in the next column (right).  If the target
     column is shorter, clamps to its last card.
‘S-TAB’
     Move to the same row in the previous column (left), with the same
     clamping behaviour.

   Standard Emacs keys (‘C-n’/‘C-p’ or arrow keys) work for vertical
navigation.  The convenience keys ‘n’/‘p’ (next/prev card) and ‘f’/‘b’
(next/prev column) are also available.

   The card under point is highlighted with bold face, providing visual
feedback for which card is active.

12.3 Actions
============

‘RET’
     Jump to the annotation's source file and position.
‘s’
     Set the card's status via ‘completing-read’.
‘}’
     Move the card one status column to the right (e.g. open ⇒
     in-progress).
‘{’
     Move the card one status column to the left (e.g. in-progress ⇒
     open).
‘g’
     Refresh the board in place, preserving cursor position.
‘q’
     Quit the kanban buffer.

   Plain string annotations (legacy format) are automatically converted
to thread format when their status is changed from the board.

12.4 Filtering
==============

The kanban board supports three filters that can be combined (AND
logic).  Active filters are shown in the header line with green
highlighting.

‘a’
     Filter by author.  Select from authors present in the current
     board, or choose ‘[All]’ to clear.
‘l’
     Filter by annotation level (‘file’, ‘defun’, ‘line’).  Select a
     level or ‘[All]’ to clear.
‘t’
     Filter by tag.  Select from tags present in the current board, or
     choose ‘[All]’ to clear.
‘d’
     Clear the directory filter (widening a dired-narrowed board back to
     the whole project).

   Filters stack: for example, pressing ‘a’ to select an author and then
‘t’ to select a tag shows only cards by that author with that tag.

12.5 Expand and Follow
======================

‘e’
     Toggle expanded view for the card at point.  Expanded cards show
     full annotation text, tags, and reply count.
‘E’
     Toggle expand/collapse for all cards at once.
‘F’
     Toggle follow mode.  When on, navigating between cards
     automatically shows the annotation source in another window.


